Jungle mynas are {{convert|23|cm|in|adj=on}} long and have grey [[Feather|plumage]], darker on the head and wings. The sexes are indistinguishable in plumage. A large white wing patches on the base of the primaries becomes conspicuous in flight, and the tail feathers are broadly tipped in white. There is a tuft of feathers on the forehead arising at the base of the bill. The bill and legs are bright yellow, and there is no bare skin around eye as in the [[common myna]] and the [[bank myna]]. The base of the beak is dark in adults with a shade of blue at the base of the lower mandible. The southern Indian population has a blue iris. The northeastern Indian populations have a smoky dark belly and vent. Juveniles are browner with a pale throat and along the median of the underside.<ref name=":0">{{cite book|author1=Rasmussen, P.C.|author2=Anderton, J.C.|year=2005|title=Birds of South Asia. The Ripley Guide. Volume 2: Attributes and status.|page=584|publisher=Smithsonian Institution and Lynx Edicions}}</ref>

Abnormal [[Leucism|leucistic]] plumages have been recorded.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Finn, F|year=1902|title=On some cases of abrupt variation in Indian birds|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/35558658|journal=Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal|volume=71|issue=2|pages=81–85}}</ref>
[[Image:Acridotheres fuscus south.jpg|thumb|upright|left|''A. f. mahrattensis'' with blue iris]]
The calls of the jungle myna are higher pitched than those of the common myna.<ref name="hbk" /> Foraging flocks make clipped cheeping contact calls.<ref name=":0" />

The jungle myna is part of the ''Acridotheres'' clade which is thought to have speciated in the late Pliocene and Pleistocene Periods. Unlike the starlings in the genus ''Sturnus'', they do not have well-developed adaptations including the musculature required for prying or open bill probing (which need muscles to open the beak apart forcefully).<ref name=phylo /> The nominate population ''A. f. fuscus'' was described from Bengal by [[Johann Georg Wagler|Wagler]] as ''Pastor fuscus'' in 1827. It has a pale creamy vent. This population with a yellow iris extends south of the Brahmaputra into Burma and the Malay Peninsula. ''A. f. fumidus'' of eastern India, mainly east of the Brahmaputra in Assam and Nagaland (although movements are known),<ref>{{cite journal| journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society| year=2007| volume=104| issue=1| title=Range Extension of Jungle Myna Acridotheres fuscus fumidus|author1=Chatterjee, S.|author2=Sen, S.K.|author3=Ghose, D.|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48382448}}</ref> was described by [[Sidney Dillon Ripley]] in 1950, although he placed it as a subspecies of ''cristatellus'' based on the prevailing treatment of the time.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Ripley, S.D.|year=1950|title=Notes on Indian birds. III. Birds from Assam|url=https://archive.org/details/postilla150peab|journal=Postilla|volume=1|pages=[https://archive.org/details/postilla150peab/page/n246 1]–4}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Amadon, Dean|year=1956|title=Remarks on the starlings, family Sturnidae.|journal=American Museum Novitates|issue=1803|pages=32–34|hdl=2246/5410}}</ref> It has a darker smoky grey vent and can appear similar to the syntopic [[great myna]], but the latter is darker and does not have a pale iris.. The peninsular Indian population ''mahrattensis'' described by [[William Henry Sykes|W.H. Sykes]] in 1832 is identifiable by the blue iris.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14485486|title=Check-list of birds of the World. Volume 15.|volume=v.15 (1962)|publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology|year=1962|editor1=Mayr, E.|place=Cambridge, MA|pages=113–114|editor2=Greenway, James C. Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|author=Marien, Daniel |year=1950|title= Notes on some Asiatic Sturnidae (birds)| journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society| volume=49| issue=3| pages=471–487|url= https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48181979}}</ref> The population in the Malay Peninsula, ''torquatus'', was described by [[William Ruxton Davison|W.R. Davison]] in 1892. It has a white throat and a half-collar extending around the neck.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Davison, W.R.|year=1892|title=Descriptions of some new species of birds from the eastern coast of the Malayan Peninsula|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/16188175|journal=Ibis|series=6|volume=4|issue=13|pages=99–103|doi=10.1111/j.1474-919X.1892.tb01189.x}}</ref> The species has a diploid chromosome number of 74 (80 in the [[common myna]]).<ref>{{cite journal| url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/cytologia1929/45/3/45_3_403/_pdf|title=Somatic chromosomes of Acridotheres fuscus fuscus Wagler and Acridotheres tristis tristis Linnaeus| journal=Cytologia| volume=45| pages=403–410| year=1980| author1=Sharma, G.P.|author2=Mittal, O.P.| author3=Gupta, N.|issue=3|doi=10.1508/cytologia.45.403| doi-access=free}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Jungle Myna- Taking off I3 IMG 2369 (cropped).jpg|thumb|The white of the base of the primaries and the tips of the tail are visible in flight]]
The jungle myna is a common resident breeder in tropical southern [[Asia]] from [[Nepal]], [[Bangladesh]], [[India]]. Subspecies ''fuscus'' is found across northern India west from [[Mount Abu]], east to [[Puri]] in Orissa.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Majumdar, N|year=1981|title=Extension of range of the Indian Maroonbreasted sunbird, ''Nectarinia lotenia hindustanica'' (Whistler) [Aves, Nectariniidae], and the Northern Jungle Myna, ''Acridotheres fuscus fuscus'' (Wagler) [Aves, Sturnidae]|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48228911|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=78|issue=2|pages=383–384}}</ref> It has also been introduced into the Andaman Islands and Fiji where it was introduced around 1890 to control insect pests in sugarcane.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Pernetta, John C.|author2=Watling, D.|year=1978|title=The introduced and native terrestrial vertebrates of Fiji|url=https://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/bitstream/10125/1436/1/v32n3-223-244.pdf|journal=Pacific Science|volume=32|issue=3|pages=223–244}}</ref> They have expanded on their own into some Pacific Islands such as [[Niuafoʻou|Niuafo'ou]] where they are a threat to native bird species such as lories (''[[Vini (genus)|Vini]]'') with whom they compete especially for nest holes.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rinke|first=Dieter|date=1986|title=The status of wildlife in Tonga|journal=Oryx|language=en|volume=20|issue=3|pages=146–151|doi=10.1017/S0030605300019980|issn=1365-3008|doi-access=free}}</ref> In many parts of Asia, they are kept as pets and feral populations have established in many places such as in Taiwan.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Shieh, Bao-Sen|author2=Lin, Ya-Hui|author3=Lee, Tsung-Wei|author4=Chang, Chia-Chieh|author5=Cheng, Kuan-Tzou|title=Pet Trade as Sources of Introduced Bird Species in Taiwan|url=http://tai2.ntu.edu.tw/Taiwania/pdf/tai.2006.51.81.pdf|journal=Taiwania|volume=51|issue=2|pages=81–86|archive-date=10 August 2017|access-date=18 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170810091921/http://tai2.ntu.edu.tw/taiwania/pdf/tai.2006.51.81.pdf}}</ref> Breeding populations have established in Japan<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Eguchi, K.|author2=Amano, H.E.|year=2004|title=Spread of exotic birds in Japan|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/osj/3/1/3_1_3/_pdf|journal=Ornithological Science|volume=3|pages=3–11|doi=10.2326/osj.3.3|doi-access=free}}</ref> and Western Samoa.<ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Evans|first1=S. M.|last2=Fletcher|first2=F. J. C.|last3=Loader|first3=P. J.|last4=Rooksby|first4=F. G.|date=1992|title=Habitat exploitation by landbirds in the changing Western Samoan environment|journal=Bird Conservation International|language=en|volume=2|issue=2|pages=123–129|doi=10.1017/S0959270900002355|issn=1474-0001|doi-access=free}}</ref> The population ''torquatus'' of Malaysia is on the decline and is possibly being outcompeted by Javan mynas with which it form hybrids.<ref name="malay" />

This common [[passerine]] is typically found in forest and cultivation and often close to open water. They may disperse outside their range particularly after the breeding season.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Dhindsa, Manjit S|author2= Singhal, R.N.|year=1983| title=Occurrence of the Northern Jungle Myna ''Acridotheres fuscus'' Wagler in the Punjab and Haryana| journal= J. Bombay Nat. Hist. Soc.|volume=80|issue=2| pages=416–417| url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48744026}}</ref>

== Behaviour and ecology ==
[[Image:The Greater one horned Rhinoceros.jpg|thumb|left|A perched cattle egret and fluttering jungle myna pick off parasites and insects from the external skin of this Indian rhinocerous in Chitwan National Park, Nepal.]]
Jungle mynas are omnivorous feed mainly on insects, fruit and seeds, for which they forage mainly on the ground often in the company of other myna species. They also take berries from low bushes such as ''[[Lantana camara|Lantana]]'' and take nectar from large flowers borne on trees such as ''[[Erythrina]]'' (which they may also pollinate with their tuft feathers acting as brushes) and water collected in the flowers of introduced trees such ''[[Spathodea|Spathodea campanulata]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Watling, R.J.|year=1975|title=Observations on the ecological separation of two introduced congeneric mynahs (Acridotheres) in Fiji|url=https://www.notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_22_1.pdf#page=41|journal=Notornis|volume=22|issue=1|pages=37–53|archive-date=3 November 2021|access-date=18 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211103144853/https://www.notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_22_1.pdf#page=41}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author1=Raju, Aluri J. S.|author2=Rao, S.P.|year=2004|title=Passerine bird pollination and fruiting behaviour in a dry season blooming tree species, Erythrina suberosa Roxb. (Fabaceae) in the Eastern Ghats forests, India|url=https://www.jstage.jst.go.jp/article/osj/3/2/3_2_139/_pdf|journal=Ornithological Science|volume=3|issue=2|pages=139–144|doi=10.2326/osj.3.139|doi-access=free}}</ref> They also perch on large grazing mammals, picking ectoparasites off their bodies,<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sazima|first=Ivan|date=2011|title=Cleaner birds: a worldwide overview|url=http://repositorio.unicamp.br/bitstream/REPOSIP/55989/1/WOS000305115000004.pdf|journal=Revista Brasileira de Ornitologia|volume=19|issue=1|pages=32–47|access-date=18 October 2018|archive-date=18 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018122501/http://repositorio.unicamp.br/bitstream/REPOSIP/55989/1/WOS000305115000004.pdf}}</ref> and capturing insects that may be disturbed into flight from vegetation. Flocks may also follow farmers in fields that are being ploughed. They also forage on kitchen waste in urban areas.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/dli.zoological.occpapers.044/page/n71|title=A contribution to the food habits of some Indian Mynas (Aves). (Records of the Zoological Survey of India Miscellaneous Publication Occasional Paper, 44.|author1=Narang, M.L.|author2=Lamba, B.S.|publisher=Zoological Survey of India|year=1984|place=Calcutta}}</ref> They may take larger prey including small mice to feed their young.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Johnsingh, A.J.T.|year= 1979|title= A note on the predation of Jungle Myna (Acridotheres fuscus Wagler) on field mouse|journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural Historical Society|volume= 76|page=159|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48240520}}</ref> In Fiji, they have been noticed [[Anting (bird activity)|anting]] using a millipede.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Clunie, F.|year=1976|title=Jungle Mynah "anting" with a millipede|url=https://www.notornis.osnz.org.nz/system/files/Notornis_23_1.pdf|journal=Notornis|volume=23|page=77}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|author=Neelakantan, K.K.|year=1974|title=Jungle Mynas ''Acridotheres fuscus'' anting|journal= Newsletter for Birdwatchers|volume=14|issue=5|pages=8–9}}</ref>

The breeding season is in summer and before the rains, February to May in southern India and April to July in northern India.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/BakerFbiBirds3|title=The Fauna of British India, including Ceylon and Burma. Birds. Volume III|author=Baker, E.C.S.|publisher=Taylor and Francis|year=1926|edition=2|place=Lonon|pages=[https://archive.org/details/BakerFbiBirds3/page/n78 57]–58}}</ref> They are secondary cavity nesters, using both holes in trees and in man-made constructions such as walls, embankments, and in houses from 2 to 6 metres above the ground.  As secondary tree hole nesters, they compete with other hole-nesters.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Jha, Aniruddha|year=2001|title=Competition between jungle myna Acridotheres fuscus and lesser golden backed woodpecker Dinopium benghalense for a nest hole|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48583324|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=98|page=115}}</ref> They have also been recorded using the axils of fronds of palm trees in Malaysia.<ref name="malay">{{cite book|title=The Birds of the Thai-Malay Peninsula, Volume 2|author=Wells, David R.|publisher=Bloomsbury Publishing|year=2010|pages=457–459}}</ref> They sometimes use sloughed snake skins to line the inside of the nest hole.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Breeding of the southern jungle myna Acridotheres fuscus mahrattensis (Sykes) at Karanja|volume=95| year=1998| journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society| page=346|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48604888 |author1=Unnithan, Saraswathy| author2=Unnithan, G.V.K.}}</ref> In the Himalayan foothills, they use dry pine needles to line the nest.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Mukherjee, RN|year=1970|title=Jungle Mynas and their nests|url=https://archive.org/details/NLBW10|journal=Newsletter for Birdwatchers|volume=10|issue=10|page=[https://archive.org/details/NLBW10/page/n50 11]}}</ref> The usual clutch consists of 4 to 6 turquoise blue eggs. Both sexes take part in nest building, incubation and feeding the young.<ref name="hbk" />

They roost communally along with other mynas, sometimes in sugarcane fields and reed beds.<ref name="hbk">{{cite book|title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan. Volume 5. Larks to the Grey Hypocolius|author1=Ali Salim|author2=Ripley, S. Dillon|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1987|edition=2|place=Delhi|pages=183–187}}</ref>

Species of ''[[Haemoproteus]]'' are known from the blood of mynas and they have also been found to host ''[[Plasmodium circumflexum]]'' when artificially infected in the lab.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Laird, Marshall|author2=Lari, Faiyaz A.|year=1958|title=Observations on Plasmodium circumflexum Kikuth and P. vaughani Novy and Macneal from East Pakistan|journal=The Journal of Parasitology|volume=44|issue=2|pages=136–152 |doi=10.2307/3274690|jstor=3274690|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last1=Ishtiaq|first1=Farah|last2=Gering|first2=Eben|last3=Rappole|first3=Jon H.|last4=Rahmani|first4=Asad R.|author5-link=Yadvendradev Vikramsinh Jhala|last5=Jhala|first5=Yadvendradev V.|last6=Dove|first6=Carla J.|last7=Milensky|first7=Chris|last8=Olson|first8=Storrs L.|last9=Peirce|first9=Mike A.|date=2007|title=Prevalence and diversity of avian hematozoan parasites in Asia: a regional survey|journal=Journal of Wildlife Diseases|language=EN|volume=43|issue=3|pages=382–398|doi=10.7589/0090-3558-43.3.382|pmid=17699077|issn=0090-3558|doi-access=free}}</ref> Other parasites that have been found in the jungle myna include ''[[Dorisa]] aethiopsaris'' in the intestine.<ref>{{cite book|page=[https://archive.org/details/dli.zoological.sfs.018/page/n337 334]|title= Fauna of West Bengal. Part 12. Protozoa|publisher=Zoological Survey of India|year=1993|chapter=Parasitic Protozoa|author1=Das, A.K.|author2=Mandal, A.K.|author3=Nandi, N.C.| author4=Nandi, R.|author5=Sarkar, N.C.|chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/dli.zoological.sfs.018}}</ref>

